      <title>Re: Two AAs I see that a lot of tanks lack and tis not a good thing.</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&amp;message.id=14056#M14056</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
Tornicade_IV wrote:&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;any properly geared tank at 65 should have about 150-300 aa at 65 .&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Actually, any approach is going to get you the same means to an end.&amp;nbsp; Either you grind out AAs at lower levels slightly slower and have an easier time taking on more challenging content as you level... or you grind out levels with some difficulty, and then raise your AAs at a faster rate... or you mix n' match.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Levels still give your character greater overall power than most AA skills, as it allows you to generally raise skillcaps, and change the level difference between the you and the mobs you're fighting.....&amp;nbsp;AND the ability to&amp;nbsp;train some more powerful AA abilities (ironic, isn't it?)&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Balancing AAs and Levels is like balancing your gear... at first you look at it like, do I go for AC? HP? avoidance? shielding?... should I get faction here, look for rare drops here... and it all looks like so much to do all at once.&amp;nbsp; Just take your time, plan out what you think will be the greatest benefit to you and go for it...&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Unless you throw your exp into innate &amp;lt;insert random unused stat&amp;gt;... you really can't go wrong if you know how your class works.&lt;/P&gt;</description>
